µC1µF1µJEOnce upon a time...

All good stories begin with these words. So, once upon a time the german system operator and former phreaker µC2DigimanµC1 visited Acid Slams` ex sysop µC3Pyro µC1at his flat in Hamburg. The new years day came near and he wanted to buy some cheap rockets from him. At the wall were written down many phone numbers of active and retired Scene people.

And in a good moment, when Pyro was out of his room, Digiman used the chance and wrote down the number of a person he thought he would know. The handle of the guy he noticed was µC4CapµC1. But it was a completly different mate than he thought it would be. Days later he decided to dial this number and was really surprised when he had a totally unknown fellow at the other side of the phone. This Cap was a former member of the ex german Amiga cracking and training group Supplex and was shortly before finishing his studies in computer science.

Both spoke with each others a long time, had a nice chat - and Digiman was successful in making Cap curious to see what would go on in the current Scene, so many years after he called up a bbs the last time. What then happened can be explained in some short terms. Cap had a look at µC3Acid Slam BBSµC1, visited some other boards and Sceneportals in the net and began to look out for everybody he knew before.

Not many but still some friends from the past were reachable. Well, and then obviously he took the decision to reopen Supplex again. But where? On which platform does it make sense to do so? The Amiga is practically dead when it comes to its illegal Scene. Cap shortly before found out that the PC warez Scene sucked like hell in his opinion, and then had a closer look at the illegal GBA (Game Boy Advanced) Scene.

Games looking like old OCS majors on the Amiga 500, only a hand full of groups that make it easier to get a general idea of the Scene. And a sort of elitism he liked so much. GBA group leaders have their strict rules and everything looked really inviting for him.
µC7MelvinµC1 (ex-Rebels) and µC6ExhorderµC1, better known as "The Cheese Thief" from the µC3Cologne Conference '99µC1 and a wellknown party boozer in Germany, joined up as he was also a member of Supplex a long time ago and became co-organizer.

Then a lot of ftp siteops and sysops of telnet boards were invited to come in.

µC2"The whole ftp Scene is really utterly worse with only a few exceptions, people like µC3SteelµC1 or µC4Shallow.µC1 (editors note:Both have their origins in the Amiga cracking Scene) The others are mostly 14 years old kids operating those ftp sites. That are people that doesn't know anything how great it was in the past, people without respect for their own roots."

µC2"But after hanging around in telnet boards, and all of them have a damn slow µC2connection, I changed my opinion and began trading between ftp sites"µC1, a smiling Cap told us via phone. Supplex has them both and broke the unwritten rule to mention the names of the sites they own. µC2"I simply don't care what the others think. May they think we suck! Mentioning their names in the .nfo of the release is simply oldskoolish!". µC1In the GBA Scene this didn't make them popular but still wellknown. After a few good releases and the chance to spread them directly at the leading sites, nobody was able to dupe their majors or overlook this crew anymore.

The future doesn`t look so bad at all. Cap had loads of great plans with his group. µC2"Maybe we will in the distant future port the GBA charts into an executable chartsmag, if not diskmag. The charts have been released as a textfile, which could be made better." µC1He's been in close contact with he makers of the GBA charts, the panels were in the making. But the whole thing was dropped again.

As Supplex wasn't able to release anything on gba except british versions of american games and nobody was found to make the code of the charts, these plans had to be fallen down again. In the meantime the group decided to concentrate on releasing Ebooks. Surely also because the competition isn't the biggest in this sort of Scene.

The big bustwaves of the GVU (µC3Gesellschaft zur Verfolgung von Urheberrechtsverletzungen = German Federation Against Copyright TheftµC1) & FBI (µC0federal bureau of investigationsµC1) in Spring and Summer of 2004 didn't make it easier to communicate and to find sites. Many german people have completly left the Scene or cutted down their activity to a minimum as it became quite dangerous to flash between german ftp sites.

Some months ago Cap decided to seek out for demosceners at major news stations such as Ojuice or the SNN to join in and dared to open an official homepage at µC6http://www.supplex.comµC1, which is still under construction.

An own pdf-based ebook magazine with releasing charts could become reality in the distant future. But right now nothing happened, nothing is sure. We just have to wait and see what will happen next...

