When it comes to the Zevi (c64), I`d like to advertise for the fantastic article "The Beginning" of Jeff Smart in issue seven of the C64 diskmag Attitude by Oxyron. Jeff Smart has been a software pirate on this computer around µC0TWENTY YEARS AGO!!µC1 Reading a c64 mag on a PC is very easy. Install the emulator VICE (http://www.viceteam.org), search for the product you`re hunting for at pouet.net. Download it, use the option "autostart disk/tape image", press left ALT & D for the fullscreen mode and - BANG - There you have your c64!! A brotkasten in full effect! Btw.: The same can surely be done with c64 emulators for the Amiga. ;-)

Why I mention this article right now? Pretty easy, because Jeff also speaks in his endless long and totally fascinating article how he did meet Irata at some parties. Can you imagine that? This is nearly as long ago as the average age of nowadays PC Sceners roughly is. Maybe I exaggerate it now a bit, but if you think that I`m an old man, look at Irata how many years he`s been acting in the Scene!!!

My deepest respect, pal!!




µC2Endless up `n down curves!µC1

For many years he did tend to join the Scene for a few months, left it after a short while, and then made a long break before he came back. In the past the main reason was that he seemingly wasn't able to control his trading activities. So his first or second phonebill "stopped" him. But thank god in the time where only the net plays an important role, that isn't possible (& necessary) anymore.

µC3IrataµC1 took a good nose of the current Scene, like others take a good nose of "white snow", and decided to reactivate his group aswell. The german coder/cracker µC4CrazyµC1 of Radwar & Trsi made a trainermenu & crackintro for the GBA, and the µC2Acid Slam BBSµC1 became an active Trsi headquarter again.


In March 2003 Kozmik of Trsi released "Mikado" at Equinoxe, a mediocre demo for the PC, which sadly doesn't work correctly on my system. It was totally thumbed down at Pouet but as said, I can`t judge it by myself as it quits after a minute running or so.

Also in March `03 they kicked an Amiga game, "Crossfire II", some new Fame tools from Siegel and some trainers for big N's handheld. A month before a GBA intro called "Oldschool Memories" coded by Duke has been kicked out. A good start for the revival of a phenomenal, old group I'd say.
Sorry, I don`t know exactly when (as Irata never replied my questions for the interview), but somewhen Irata took µC0Doc D.µC1 of Digital on board for the management and announced a cooperation between them and Fairlight, mostly with the demo section of Flt. µC2KozmikµC1, the coder of that strange Trsi demo was kicked. µC3PahnµC1, wellknown from the irc.net channel #amielite aswell and then the wellknown editor µC7DarkusµC1 decided to leave the boat, too.

Obviously µC6MagicµC1 felt a bit sick about that teamwork as "his" group (Nah-Kolor) was a subgroup of Trsi many years ago. In 1995 the management of TRSI decided to break the relationship with Nah as they saw it as being useless and bringing bad public relations to the name & reputation of TRSI. Bad luck for Magic!


µC2And now, what`s recently going on?µC1

Some new bulletin board systems and their sysops were taken over. A section in the USA with new people has been build. µC0TCBµC1, once famous for being a member of Global Overdose, a very good Amiga cracking & training group from Belgium is nowadays a member of Quartex. The oldskool legend Quartex & TRSI are now also co-operating.

The british Pouet.net clown, µC7ShaneµC1-the-Idiot(not the wolfMan) in October 2004 annouced at the Pouet forum that he`s the new leader of Trsi. Well, none of the Pouet gloeppers took it (and it wasn`t meant) seriously.
But the new crackintro for Windows, kicked out together with Hoodlum, was serious and very nice. Oups, I nearly forgot to mention a small intro from Assembly 2004 "1k-sw-raytrace`em all" and last but not least the CD image for Playstation II with fucking many C64 games on it! What a funky idea, I must say!! Extremly modern technology combined with funny old games. Just imagine to play "Defender of the crown" or "Winter Games" on a PS2!! Yes, not each of the thousands of games being burned on that CD are worth to play, but many are.
Now only some more illegal releases are missing (especially they should be fresher than those zevi games ;-) And then everything would be in movement.

